refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.changelog;
&Version; &Description;
4.1.0
The shutdown functions are now called as a part of the request. In earlier versions under Apache, the registered shutdown functions were called after the request has been completed (including sending any output buffers), so it was not possible to send output to the browser using echo or print, or retrieve the contents of any output buffers using ob_get_contents. Headers were also always already sent.

  &reftitle.examples;



    register_shutdown_function example


<?php
function shutdown()
{
    // This is our shutdown function, in 
    // here we can do any last operations
    // before the script is complete.

    echo 'Script executed with success', PHP_EOL;
}

register_shutdown_function('shutdown');
?>

&reftitle.notes;
Typically undefined functions cause fatal errors in PHP, but when the function called with register_shutdown_function is undefined, an error of level E_WARNING is generated instead. Also, for reasons internal to PHP, this error will refer to Unknown at line #0.
Working directory of the script can change inside the shutdown function under some web servers, e.g. Apache.
